<%# Docs chapter 02 — the fingerprints. Embeddings and cosine similarity
    in plain words. Copy rule: simple words, no hyphens in visible text. %>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <%- include('../partials/head', { title: 'The fingerprints — how it works' }) %>
</head>
<body class="min-h-screen bg-paper font-sans text-ink antialiased">
  <%- include('../partials/frame') %>
  <%- include('../partials/nav') %>

  <main class="relative mx-auto max-w-6xl overflow-hidden px-6 py-12">
    <span class="pointer-events-none absolute -right-10 top-6 select-none font-serif text-[15rem] font-extrabold leading-none text-ink/[0.04]" aria-hidden="true">指</span>

    <div class="reveal relative">
      <%- include('../partials/docs-header') %>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          The hardest part of recommending stories is that stories are made
          of meaning, and computers are made of numbers. Matching keywords
          fails in both directions: two shows can share the word "ocean"
          and have nothing in common, and two quiet shows about wandering
          healers can share no words at all. This chapter explains the
          piece of the engine that solves that, and it is the headline
          signal of the whole system.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12">
        <span class="font-serif text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">地図</span>
        <span class="jp-sub">chizu — a map of meaning</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          A small language model, about eighty megabytes, runs on our own
          machine. No keys, no cloud, no cost, and no synopsis ever leaves
          the site to be read. The model reads a summary and answers with a
          list of <strong>384 numbers</strong>. That list is called an
          embedding, and the friendliest way to picture it is as an address
          on an enormous map of meaning. Every text lands somewhere on that
          map, and texts that talk about similar things land near each
          other, even when they share no vocabulary.
        </p>
        <p>
          The numbers themselves mean nothing to a human, and that is fine.
          What matters is the geometry: revenge stories gather in one
          region, gentle countryside stories in another, time travel plots
          in a third. The model learned that geometry from reading a very
          large amount of text, and we simply borrow its sense of
          direction.
        </p>
        <p>
          Before any text is read, markup is stripped out so the model sees
          prose, not code. Titles are deliberately left out of the reading:
          a romanized name tells you almost nothing about a story, and
          feeding it in would only add noise. And one honest limit: the
          model reads English, so the rare entry whose only summary is in
          another language gets a blurry fingerprint until better text
          exists for it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12">
        <span class="font-serif text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">平均</span>
        <span class="jp-sub">heikin — two readings, one portrait</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          Chapter one explained why each anime carries two summaries: the
          fan voice and the encyclopedia voice. The engine fingerprints
          each text separately, then stores the average of the two: the
          point on the map that sits halfway between them. A summary that
          leans hard on mood and a summary that leans hard on plot pull the
          portrait toward the middle, and the middle is closer to what the
          show actually is than either text alone. When only one summary
          exists, its fingerprint stands alone, which is still good, just
          less rounded.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12">
        <span class="font-serif text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">角度</span>
        <span class="jp-sub">kakudo — comparing two stories</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          To compare two anime, picture each fingerprint as an arrow
          pointing out from the center of the map. The engine measures the
          <strong>angle between the two arrows</strong>. Two arrows
          pointing the same way mean two stories about the same kind of
          thing, and they score near the top. Arrows at right angles mean
          the stories are unrelated. The score does not care how long the
          arrows are, only where they point, which is exactly right: a long
          rambling synopsis and a short sharp one should still match if
          they describe the same kind of tale.
        </p>
        <p>
          This measurement is cheap on purpose. The fingerprints live
          inside the database itself, next to the rest of each anime's row,
          and comparing one show against all
          <span class="tabular-nums">38,000</span> others takes well under
          a millisecond. That speed is why the red thread can be computed
          fresh on every page view, with whatever slider mix you choose,
          instead of being precomputed and stale.
        </p>
      </div>

      <%- include('../partials/docs-pager') %>
    </div>
  </main>

  <%- include('../partials/footer') %>
</body>
</html>
